WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.980
All right. Well, I think we'll get started.

2
00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:04.910
Welcome, everyone, to this educational session

3
00:00:06.260 --> 00:00:08.570
on multimodal platforms for early cancer detection.

4
00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:12.480
I think that this topic is going to be an exciting one at this year's

5
00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:16.440
AACR, and I'm really, really honored to be joined by two

6
00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:20.320
really amazing speakers, I think, to talk about this topic today.

7
00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:23.280
So if you would like to ask questions in this

8
00:00:23.300 --> 00:00:26.800
session, you can either come to the mics.

9
00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:30.380
It is important for you to come up to the microphone, given the live stream, and

10
00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.000
speak into the microphone. Also, you can put your questions by using this

11
00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:37.440
QR code here. So I'll leave that here for just a second,

12
00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:39.760
so people can take a picture of it.

13
00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:43.760
All right. That was definitely just one second.

14
00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:45.180
So

15
00:00:46.060 --> 00:00:49.200
in way of introduction, my name is Kara Maxwell.

16
00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:53.000
I'm at the University of Pennsylvania, and I'm just going to do two quick

17
00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:55.820
introduction slides to the topic that we're trying to talk about today.

18
00:00:56.180 --> 00:01:00.160
So it's no secret to anybody in the multi-cancer early detection space that

19
00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:03.760
what we're trying to do is really improve upon early

20
00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:07.320
detection as a way to reduce cancer morbidity and mortality.

21
00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:11.380
I'm from the University of Pennsylvania, and we have a saying by Ben Franklin,

22
00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:14.080
that an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure.

23
00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:18.180
I give kudos to Dr. Bob Vonderheide, our cancer center director, as

24
00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:21.930
the first one that introduced me to that, but I really do believe that that is how

25
00:01:21.930 --> 00:01:23.990
we're going to make the needle forward.

26
00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:28.300
Right now, we have screening programs in this country for a few

27
00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:32.240
different cancers, namely lung cancer in certain folks

28
00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.110
at risk, breast cancer, and colorectal cancer, and cervical cancer for the general

29
00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.650
population. But as we know, each of these tests is an

30
00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:43.480
individual test, and so the promise of a blood-based test where we could detect

31
00:01:43.560 --> 00:01:46.200
multiple cancers at once really is the dream.

32
00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:50.980
There's been a lot of movement forward in this field, and I think one of the things

33
00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:54.250
that is obviously concerning to many of us is what is the sensitivity and

34
00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:58.250
specificity of these tests that are coming out, and are we actually going

35
00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:01.880
to be able to handle the tests that come out of it?

36
00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:06.130
So this is a graph that came out in the Science Bulletin, by Dr.

37
00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:09.150
Zhu and colleagues that I really think is nice, and it sort of balances.

38
00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:12.920
Almost all of these multi-cancer early detection tests that we have right now have

39
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.560
very high specificity, but we're still a little

40
00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.100
bit failing on the specificity side.

41
00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:22.680
Just as a component of this as well, though, it's important to talk about that the

42
00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:25.420
tumor of origin is a very important component of this.

43
00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:28.120
Unlike mammography, you know what you're screening for.

44
00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:31.620
In this case, we also need the accuracy of the prediction.

45
00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:35.740
And just as a reminder, I just put some stars here on sort

46
00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:39.290
of well-considered sensitivity and

47
00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:41.780
specificity for our current screening programs.

48
00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:46.140
And specificity is not quite as high as maybe some of the

49
00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:50.040
early detection tests out there, but the sensitivity of these tests is still a

50
00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:52.090
little bit higher than what we are currently working at.

51
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:55.740
So what we're going to talk about today, and I'm joined by two really exciting

52
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:59.280
experts in this field, is maybe what we need to do is start to move the needle

53
00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:03.240
forward by considering other modalities besides just cell-free DNA,

54
00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:04.140
which has been the

55
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.920
most studied modality so far. So we're going to start with Dr.

56
00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:11.620
Martin Taylor, who's going to talk to us about one such possibility, using

57
00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:14.260
LINE1 as an early detection tool.

58
00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:19.900
Thank you so much, Dr. Maxwell. It's really great to be here.

59
00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:23.880
It's an honor, and thanks to the organizers and Dr. Maxwell for inviting me.

60
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.360
So I'm going to talk about LINE1, a pan-cancer biomarker of carcinoma and high-risk

61
00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:33.260
precursors. I'm assistant professor at Brown University, where my

62
00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:36.829
lab works on LINE1 mechanism, as well as using it in cancer

63
00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:40.660
detection. So I'll briefly go through what LINE1 is, what its

64
00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:43.700
ORF1 protein is, why we think it's a useful biomarker.

65
00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:47.940
I'll go through the technology, which to summarize, is a low-cost,

66
00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:51.900
sensitive, and specific cancer biomarker that could either be a standalone

67
00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:55.820
test in a screening paradigm or monitoring paradigm, or could work

68
00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:59.780
as part of an MSI test. We use ultrasensitive

69
00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:03.769
single molecule detection of the LINE1 encoded ORF1 protein from

70
00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:07.360
biofluids for cancer detection. It is a unique

71
00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:09.680
biomarker because of the transposon biology.

72
00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:12.720
The LINE1 is pervasively expressed in cancer and not in healthy tissues, and I will

73
00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:16.500
show you that. And the assays are very inexpensive and use very little

74
00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:18.329
blood and can be run in under two hours,

75
00:04:19.161 --> 00:04:22.700
which makes them quite different from many of the other platforms and potentially

76
00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:25.920
could find them a unique niche. So I'll go through the assay.

77
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.510
I'll tell you some of the future things we're doing, where we can look in other

78
00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:33.530
kinds of biofluids, where we've shown some utility in cancer monitoring, and

79
00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:35.350
what we're trying to do in the detection space.

80
00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:39.660
So, actually only 2% of the genome is

81
00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:43.340
protein coding genes or protein coding exons, even less than 1%.

82
00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:46.900
The rest has been called the dark genome, and we only know the function of a

83
00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:47.740
fraction of it.

84
00:04:48.740 --> 00:04:52.120
But half of it is roughly three million copies of the same few

85
00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:55.860
retroelement virus-like self-copying sequences over and over

86
00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:59.600
again. And of those, in humans, only one is still active.

87
00:04:59.630 --> 00:05:02.890
It's called LINE1, and it's a virus-like self-copying parasite,

88
00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:07.160
and we've been evolving with LINE1 and its precursors for more than two billion

89
00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:11.160
years. It is conserved to plants. And at the end of

90
00:05:11.170 --> 00:05:15.140
a two billion year host parasite arms race, our normal healthy

91
00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.900
tissues are extremely good at keeping LINE1 off.

92
00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:22.660
But pervasively in diseases of aging and especially in cancer, LINE1

93
00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:26.380
becomes de-repressed and turns on, and this has multiple negative

94
00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:30.360
consequences. First, LINE1 causes sterile inflammation

95
00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:31.960
through a process that was called viral mimicry.

96
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.600
There was a session on that yesterday, and actually Kate Chipkin Ellie's here,

97
00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:36.360
who's one of the first people who discovered that.

98
00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.440
Secondly, LINE1 is a mutagen. It's trying to copy and paste itself someplace else

99
00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:43.940
in the genome. And in addition to the canonical mutagenic

100
00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:47.700
insertions, which themselves are a problem, we now understand that that actually

101
00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:51.070
only represents a very small fraction of attempted insertions, and that LINE1 can

102
00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:54.840
cause DNA damage and chromosomal instability on its own.

103
00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:59.084
And these together have-Been thought to contribute to the

104
00:05:59.104 --> 00:06:02.524
pathologies of a number of common human diseases of aging, and especially cancer.

105
00:06:03.304 --> 00:06:06.804
And then specifically in cancer, our work with Kathy Burns has showed that when

106
00:06:06.844 --> 00:06:10.284
LINE-1 is turned on early in carcinogenesis, before

107
00:06:10.324 --> 00:06:13.914
P53 is mutated, and I'm about to show you that that happens quite pervasively,

108
00:06:14.544 --> 00:06:18.104
LINE-1 causes a very profound P53-mediated growth arrest,

109
00:06:18.444 --> 00:06:20.164
which can cause positive selective pressure.

110
00:06:20.564 --> 00:06:24.084
And we think that this may explain, at least in part, why P53 mutations are so

111
00:06:24.104 --> 00:06:24.964
prevalent in cancer.

112
00:06:26.384 --> 00:06:30.264
So the goal of my research program in general, and of using

113
00:06:30.284 --> 00:06:34.124
LINE-1 for an early detection test, is to prevent or slow these

114
00:06:34.144 --> 00:06:37.944
diseases or find them earlier when we can intervene, and also to develop therapies,

115
00:06:37.984 --> 00:06:39.124
which I won't talk about today.

116
00:06:40.024 --> 00:06:40.204
So,

117
00:06:41.464 --> 00:06:44.804
we've known that LINE-1 could be involved in cancer and could play a role since

118
00:06:44.844 --> 00:06:48.004
1992, when Vogelstein and colleagues showed that a

119
00:06:48.024 --> 00:06:51.824
LINE-1 had jumped into an APC gene, disrupted its function, created an

120
00:06:51.864 --> 00:06:53.414
adenoma that led to a colon cancer.

121
00:06:53.924 --> 00:06:57.484
But it wasn't until, with Kathy Burns, we made the first monoclonal antibodies to

122
00:06:57.504 --> 00:07:01.374
LINE-1 and stained around 1,000 cancers at Hopkins, that it became clear that

123
00:07:01.404 --> 00:07:04.734
this was not just a one-off thing, but actually that LINE-1 was pervasively

124
00:07:04.764 --> 00:07:07.204
expressed across many different types of cancer.

125
00:07:08.094 --> 00:07:12.064
And you can see, for example, in this colon cancer, the cancer stained strongly

126
00:07:12.104 --> 00:07:15.704
for the encoded ORF1 protein. It's a chaperone protein, and the

127
00:07:15.744 --> 00:07:18.564
adjacent normal tissue from which the cancer arose is negative.

128
00:07:19.024 --> 00:07:22.004
And this was true across all of the tissues that we studied.

129
00:07:22.374 --> 00:07:25.624
The normal tissues do not express LINE-1, and cancers do.

130
00:07:25.724 --> 00:07:28.594
And then in the intervening 10 years, I became a pathologist.

131
00:07:28.984 --> 00:07:32.764
We stained a lot more cases, as did a number of collaborators, especially in the

132
00:07:32.784 --> 00:07:36.714
gynecologic space. And what we learned was that actually our initial estimates were

133
00:07:36.764 --> 00:07:39.964
underestimates, in part probably because of tissue quality, in part because we

134
00:07:40.024 --> 00:07:42.664
hadn't really learned how to run the assays very well.

135
00:07:42.704 --> 00:07:46.464
And as we did that, what became very clear is that across major carcinoma

136
00:07:46.504 --> 00:07:49.724
types, LINE-1 expression is a hallmark of cancer.

137
00:07:49.804 --> 00:07:53.644
Almost all carcinomas from major types appear to express the LINE-1 ORF1 protein.

138
00:07:54.084 --> 00:07:56.604
For example, this gastric cancer, this is an intestinal type.

139
00:07:56.994 --> 00:07:59.314
You can see that the adjacent glands are totally negative.

140
00:07:59.674 --> 00:08:02.524
Same thing is true in this head and neck squamous cell carcinoma, where the

141
00:08:02.584 --> 00:08:05.984
overlying epithelium and surrounding lymphoid tissue are negative.

142
00:08:06.024 --> 00:08:07.453
And it's not just advanced cancer.

143
00:08:07.564 --> 00:08:11.024
It actually happens starting in early precursors, early lung cancers,

144
00:08:11.204 --> 00:08:14.844
precursors of pancreas cancers, STIC lesions of the ovary in the

145
00:08:14.884 --> 00:08:15.704
fallopian tube,

146
00:08:17.624 --> 00:08:20.944
and colonic adenomas, which I'll come back to in a minute, are pervasively LINE-1

147
00:08:20.964 --> 00:08:24.684
positive. And again, in immunostain after immunostain, the normal healthy

148
00:08:24.724 --> 00:08:25.624
tissue is negative.

149
00:08:27.044 --> 00:08:29.284
We showed that in Barrett's esophagus, where clinically...

150
00:08:29.464 --> 00:08:31.904
I'm a GI pathologist in practice, and

151
00:08:31.984 --> 00:08:35.744
we're really bad at esophageal cancer prevention.

152
00:08:35.824 --> 00:08:39.754
We are bad at both finding the lesion, because it's a flat lesion that goes all the

153
00:08:39.764 --> 00:08:42.264
way around the esophagus, we can't biopsy all of it.

154
00:08:42.284 --> 00:08:45.173
And then when the biopsies come out, if you put three expert GI pathologists

155
00:08:45.204 --> 00:08:48.884
together, we mostly actually disagree about the cases that matter, the intermediate

156
00:08:48.944 --> 00:08:52.694
cases. Everybody can call cancer, everybody can call normal, but the intervening is

157
00:08:52.744 --> 00:08:55.404
very challenging. And what we found with a

158
00:08:57.104 --> 00:09:01.004
cross-sectional cohort of 72 cases, that LINE-1

159
00:09:01.044 --> 00:09:04.804
pervasively marked the high-grade dysplasia, either the RNA in

160
00:09:04.844 --> 00:09:08.804
situ hybridization, which I show here, or the protein levels, and it

161
00:09:08.864 --> 00:09:09.414
was also

162
00:09:10.304 --> 00:09:11.724
pervasive in low-grade dysplasia.

163
00:09:11.764 --> 00:09:15.604
And of the indefinite cases where the GI pathologist, we can't call the case, we

164
00:09:15.624 --> 00:09:19.124
decide there's probably something wrong, but we're not sure that more attention

165
00:09:19.164 --> 00:09:22.924
should be paid. Five of the nine cases were positive for the RNA, the protein, or

166
00:09:22.944 --> 00:09:25.804
both. All five later went on to develop high-grade dysplasia, the high-risk

167
00:09:25.884 --> 00:09:28.964
precursor. So we think in summary that LINE-1

168
00:09:29.564 --> 00:09:31.324
represents high-risk precursor lesions.

169
00:09:31.924 --> 00:09:35.224
And in the stomach and gastroesophageal cancer, it's not just at the

170
00:09:35.264 --> 00:09:38.724
junction in the stomach. This is an early T1

171
00:09:39.164 --> 00:09:43.074
diffuse type gastric cancer we got from Jeremy Davis at the NIH, now at Maryland,

172
00:09:43.484 --> 00:09:45.384
and then similarly in intestinal precursors.

173
00:09:45.414 --> 00:09:47.934
And I would just point out the intestinal metaplasia here, which is also a

174
00:09:47.964 --> 00:09:50.204
recognized early precursor, is negative.

175
00:09:50.244 --> 00:09:54.184
So you have to get to a higher risk state to turn on LINE-1, at least to a

176
00:09:54.244 --> 00:09:56.764
level that we can see it at the immunohistochemistry level.

177
00:09:57.784 --> 00:10:01.044
So we just stained with Fazilet Yilmaz, a pathologist at Brown.

178
00:10:01.124 --> 00:10:04.564
We just stained a cohort of 82 polyps from 46 patients.

179
00:10:05.244 --> 00:10:09.124
In the MSS pathway, the traditional adenomas, actually all of

180
00:10:09.164 --> 00:10:13.144
them were positive, and of the serrated pathway, 19 out of

181
00:10:13.264 --> 00:10:17.004
20 dysplastic polyps were positive, whereas only about half of the

182
00:10:17.064 --> 00:10:19.854
sessile serrated adenomas without dysplasia were positive.

183
00:10:20.364 --> 00:10:23.964
And intensity of staining increased with dysplasia degree,

184
00:10:24.004 --> 00:10:27.664
indicating that LINE-1 expression is increasing throughout the carcinogenesis

185
00:10:27.724 --> 00:10:30.584
progression. Pervasively, none of the normal stained.

186
00:10:30.664 --> 00:10:34.414
So, in the colon, LINE-1 expression appears to be extremely

187
00:10:34.484 --> 00:10:38.104
pervasive, starting from the adenoma stage, and increase and mark

188
00:10:38.114 --> 00:10:39.124
higher-risk lesions.

189
00:10:40.284 --> 00:10:44.174
So going back to 2013, when Kathy and I started getting all

190
00:10:44.184 --> 00:10:47.144
of these immunostains back positive, we wondered if we could detect ORF1 in the

191
00:10:47.244 --> 00:10:50.444
blood. We had two non-overlapping antibodies.

192
00:10:50.464 --> 00:10:53.144
We got some blood from the cancer center. I made an ELISA test.

193
00:10:53.164 --> 00:10:56.964
It worked pretty well, and we never saw any LINE-1, and we moved on.

194
00:10:57.044 --> 00:11:00.184
Then, a few years ago, I met David Walt at a meeting.

195
00:11:00.264 --> 00:11:04.224
David Walt had invented microwell technology, which in addition was used

196
00:11:04.264 --> 00:11:07.124
to found a company called Illumina that I think everybody here has heard of.

197
00:11:08.254 --> 00:11:12.024
The microwell technology works by developing small wells that are

198
00:11:12.084 --> 00:11:14.934
sized to hold at most and no more than one bead.

199
00:11:15.544 --> 00:11:19.344
And what we do is we make essentially a sandwich ELISA, where we take

200
00:11:19.354 --> 00:11:22.964
a bead and we put an affinity capture reagent on the bead, bind

201
00:11:23.024 --> 00:11:26.884
into a biofluid of interest, in this case, blood or serum, and then wash

202
00:11:26.944 --> 00:11:30.444
and come in with an enzyme labeled detection antibody.

203
00:11:30.824 --> 00:11:34.644
We then load the beads into the microwells, with a fluorogenic substrate,

204
00:11:34.724 --> 00:11:35.804
seal the wells with oil,

205
00:11:36.784 --> 00:11:40.400
and simply read outIndividual molecules by counting

206
00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:44.360
fluorescence. And the assay can count one or more molecules in a well.

207
00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:47.980
As such, you make an assay that's between 1,000 and a millionfold better than a

208
00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:51.610
conventional ELISA. It's very good, a single molecule, low-level detection level.

209
00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:55.220
We applied it to a very first-generation assay.

210
00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:59.120
We applied it to about 1,000 samples from

211
00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:02.370
many different sources. And in the healthy patients, of

212
00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:06.300
406 patients, 402 of them are sitting down here

213
00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:08.380
at the limit of detection, undetectable.

214
00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:12.260
One man, who has a screamingly high value, thought he was healthy when he donated

215
00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:15.260
his blood to our biobank, and six months later was found to have an advanced

216
00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:17.180
prostate cancer metastatic up his spine.

217
00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:21.400
Of course, this was horrible for him, but we were excited because this might mean

218
00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:23.110
that we could find cancer earlier.

219
00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.910
We knew very little about these other three patients, but we were worried about

220
00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:29.680
them because across the roughly 600 cancer patients that we

221
00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:33.590
assayed at this test, half of them were positive for the line one protein in

222
00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:37.390
their blood. Importantly, we did not detect OR1 in older patients up to

223
00:12:37.560 --> 00:12:41.510
95 years old. In 30 patients with chronic liver disease, one out

224
00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:44.650
of the 30 was positive. That patient went on to have a hepatocellular carcinoma

225
00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:47.480
later. We did not find it in autoimmune conditions.

226
00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:49.530
Line one is not de-repressed in COVID-19.

227
00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:52.490
If you think that's interesting, I'd love to talk with you about why that is not

228
00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:56.150
true later. And other inflammatory conditions do not

229
00:12:56.480 --> 00:13:00.460
turn on line one. So to summarize this, we have a new kind of extremely

230
00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:04.190
specific but not yet very sensitive cancer biomarker.

231
00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:07.680
Some of these cases are early, and I'm going to come back to this in a moment.

232
00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:11.140
But I just got through telling you that on the tissue level, all of these cases

233
00:13:11.160 --> 00:13:14.080
were positive. But in the blood, we're only detecting half of them.

234
00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.170
So we had a very simple idea, which was if we could just make the assay better,

235
00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:18.540
maybe we could detect more of them.

236
00:13:19.210 --> 00:13:21.640
And so we spent a lot of time doing engineering.

237
00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:24.440
We made custom monoclonal antibodies in this application.

238
00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:27.460
We made camelid nanobodies, and I daisy-chained them together in different

239
00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:31.140
orientations to try to find optimal pairs of detection and capture

240
00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:35.550
for OR1. And we made three, what we call second-generation

241
00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:39.500
assays that use different combinations of custom capture and detection

242
00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:43.220
reagents, and we took them over a cohort of 50 women with

243
00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:47.220
ovarian cancer and 50 healthy patients that we received from Ronnie Drapkin at the

244
00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:49.019
University of Pennsylvania and the Basser Center.

245
00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:53.540
And these women, we actually did okay at the initial assay, our

246
00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:57.309
first-generation assay. About 60% of them are positive and

247
00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:00.820
including, very excitingly, four of the six early-stage ovarian cancers,

248
00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:05.260
four of five stage ones and the only stage two.

249
00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:07.360
Stage two is very rare in ovarian cancer.

250
00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:10.820
And these two healthy women are the same healthy women that are positive in all

251
00:14:10.860 --> 00:14:14.800
three, and we don't know why. But in the two newer assays, the

252
00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:18.309
second-gen assays I'm showing here, this first assay increases sensitivity,

253
00:14:18.420 --> 00:14:22.220
catching one more of the early-stage case without harming specificity.

254
00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:25.900
This other assay is actually even more sensitive, but there is a reduced

255
00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.340
specificity, but you can even see by eye that there is a cutoff here.

256
00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:33.000
And again, five of the six early stage, 83% are above the cutoff.

257
00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:36.660
And we made a mock MCED test here just combining

258
00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:40.760
HE4, CA125, and OR1P, and you can see that

259
00:14:40.780 --> 00:14:44.600
adding the OR1 test on top of the CA125 and HE4

260
00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:48.440
increases the area under the curve from 0.94 to 0.98 in this

261
00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:52.300
receiver operator setting. So this was pilot utility that we could

262
00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:55.930
show this in a multi-analyte panel, and it might help and be orthogonal to other

263
00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:56.390
methods.

264
00:14:57.400 --> 00:15:01.080
We went on to show that over about 600 cancer patients, that the

265
00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:04.670
second-generation assay had improved performance from our first-generation assay.

266
00:15:05.180 --> 00:15:08.840
It was most sensitive in ovarian cancer and also quite sensitive in colorectal

267
00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:12.500
cancer. In gastroesophageal cancer, where we have a lot of

268
00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:16.110
interest, we were only still picking up about 30% of the cases with the way this

269
00:15:16.180 --> 00:15:19.520
assay was run from 25 microliters of plasma.

270
00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:23.070
So in the intervening time, David's lab developed a new

271
00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:26.940
improved single-molecule assay detection technique called Mosaic.

272
00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:29.160
It's conceptually the same as Simoa.

273
00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:33.220
You still make the same sandwich, ELISA, but instead of needing the microwell chip,

274
00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:37.220
you build up a strong local fluorescent DNA signal on the bead with the DNA

275
00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:40.700
polymerase. And then instead of loading the beads into the chip, you run them

276
00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:43.029
through a flow cytometer. And this has a number of advantages.

277
00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:46.880
First, you don't have to have a fancy Quanterix imaging machine, which is great,

278
00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:51.060
but the chips are not totally free, and this removes the cost of the

279
00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:54.820
chip. Second, about only 10% of the beads fall into the wells of the

280
00:15:54.860 --> 00:15:57.180
chip. So this actually lets you sample all the beads.

281
00:15:57.600 --> 00:16:00.260
And in principle, you could make an assay that's at least 10% better.

282
00:16:00.839 --> 00:16:01.380
So we took

283
00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:06.140
10 healthy patients and 10 gastroesophageal cancer patients from Sam

284
00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:07.700
Klempner's bank. Sam's here in the room.

285
00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:08.620
And

286
00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:13.580
we took these, and they were selected from negative patients from our best assay

287
00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:17.320
from before, and we were able to show that nine out of 10 patients from

288
00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:21.320
cancer and none of the healthy were detectable over what was an assay background

289
00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:25.120
we had at that time. We've since improved the assay to remove the background by

290
00:16:25.180 --> 00:16:28.860
using a barcoding technology where you put in dummy beads together with the correct

291
00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:32.720
beads. And then we're able to show with this in pilot studies with

292
00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:36.240
pancreas cancer patients that we can go from detecting a little over half to

293
00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:39.370
detecting all 12 of them. So of course, we need to run more samples, but we're

294
00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:40.240
excited about this.

295
00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:41.940
So

296
00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:45.460
that's the published data. I'm going to go through a couple of new things that

297
00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:49.260
we're trying to do now. The first is that we wondered whether we could

298
00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:53.160
detect cancer early better by going not into the blood, but actually to the

299
00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:57.000
place where the cancer is. When cancer cells from the GI tract, for

300
00:16:57.020 --> 00:17:00.200
example, or in other organs die, they don't fall into the blood.

301
00:17:00.210 --> 00:17:03.600
They usually fall into the lumen, and it's actually quite clear right now that the

302
00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:07.060
best place for molecular technology for early cancer detection is in stool, where

303
00:17:07.100 --> 00:17:10.870
Cologuard is quite effective, but we're not quite yet there to utility with blood

304
00:17:10.940 --> 00:17:14.860
tests. So we're working with this technology in stool.

305
00:17:15.141 --> 00:17:19.060
And Asya in my lab also had the idea that maybe if we could recover OR1

306
00:17:19.080 --> 00:17:23.020
from alcohol-based fixatives that are commonly used for Pap smears or

307
00:17:23.040 --> 00:17:26.950
for sponge esophageal cancer samples, that might be useful for screening in

308
00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.850
ways that blood tests are challenging, that we might be able to make this work.

309
00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:33.760
But of course, in order to make this work, the protein has to be preserved in the

310
00:17:33.820 --> 00:17:37.330
alcohol. I told her there was no way this was ever going to work, but she tried it

311
00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:41.028
anyway, and I was totally wrong.So this is just a

312
00:17:41.048 --> 00:17:44.377
pilot study where she took HEK cells that were expressing LINE1 or

313
00:17:45.488 --> 00:17:49.358
GFP as a control and puts them into our best binding buffer.

314
00:17:49.428 --> 00:17:52.668
Here's the starting cells, and we have some standard curves of our purified

315
00:17:52.748 --> 00:17:56.668
protein. And then she does an IP. And she did the IP

316
00:17:56.808 --> 00:18:00.718
with either the binding buffer or by taking the OR1 that was put into

317
00:18:00.768 --> 00:18:04.738
these different thin prep cytology fixatives and freeze-thawing it, keeping it on

318
00:18:04.768 --> 00:18:08.578
her bench for a day, for a week. She's done the same thing for up to a few months

319
00:18:08.628 --> 00:18:12.428
now, and the protein is completely preserved quantitatively with no loss at all.

320
00:18:13.008 --> 00:18:16.648
Totally unexpected. So we should be able now, we think,

321
00:18:17.008 --> 00:18:19.988
to recover OR1 from these more directly accessible samples.

322
00:18:20.028 --> 00:18:23.308
For example, we would love to be able to detect ovarian and endometrial cancers

323
00:18:23.368 --> 00:18:27.338
early from Pap smears. Actually, the Vogelstein group has shown that

324
00:18:27.368 --> 00:18:30.928
you can detect tumor DNA from Pap smears more than 10 years ago,

325
00:18:31.548 --> 00:18:34.248
and it's just kind of expensive and hard for screening.

326
00:18:34.288 --> 00:18:37.548
But this assay is different in its cost-benefit ratio, we think.

327
00:18:37.588 --> 00:18:38.908
So we're hopeful that that might work.

328
00:18:39.948 --> 00:18:43.328
And then secondly, we took our existing assays in a monitoring

329
00:18:43.388 --> 00:18:47.128
context through a cohort of 19 gastroesophageal cancer patients

330
00:18:47.168 --> 00:18:50.978
undergoing therapy. Anybody who's worked with gastroesophageal cancer knows that

331
00:18:50.988 --> 00:18:54.288
during therapy it's very hard to understand what's going on with the patients.

332
00:18:54.328 --> 00:18:57.068
The tumor, the food, everything goes in the same place. It's inflamed.

333
00:18:57.108 --> 00:18:58.528
It's hard to really know what's going on.

334
00:18:59.148 --> 00:19:03.088
So we had samples at clinical presentation and between 30 and 120 days

335
00:19:03.148 --> 00:19:07.138
on therapy. And what was really striking is that

336
00:19:07.868 --> 00:19:11.228
the assay actually perfectly segregated the responders from the non-responders.

337
00:19:11.268 --> 00:19:15.118
So all of the non-responders, like this unfortunate patient whose

338
00:19:15.148 --> 00:19:18.628
tumors were growing in the liver, you can see here on the axial CT scan,

339
00:19:19.638 --> 00:19:23.508
had either residual, detectable, or an increase in their OR1 level.

340
00:19:23.628 --> 00:19:26.828
I think that one is actually this patient here who increased.

341
00:19:26.848 --> 00:19:27.078
And then

342
00:19:28.008 --> 00:19:31.708
all of the responders had their OR1 fall to undetectable at the second sample,

343
00:19:32.028 --> 00:19:34.268
like this patient whose tumor shrunk really dramatically.

344
00:19:35.688 --> 00:19:38.408
And the reviewer-- We had pointed out that the red dots are higher than the black

345
00:19:38.468 --> 00:19:42.228
dots. The reviewer was very helpful in this case and asked us to look more

346
00:19:42.248 --> 00:19:44.808
deeply. You can clearly see that

347
00:19:45.988 --> 00:19:49.008
the pretreatment biopsies are higher in the

348
00:19:49.588 --> 00:19:51.038
non-responders than the responders.

349
00:19:51.588 --> 00:19:54.848
And we ran this out over colorectal and

350
00:19:54.888 --> 00:19:58.828
gastroesophageal cancer patients, and it was extremely prognostic in the blood.

351
00:19:59.228 --> 00:20:03.148
So if you are OR1 high in the blood, like these red patients here, you do worse.

352
00:20:03.198 --> 00:20:07.028
If you're OR1 low, you do better. Now, this looks just like a ctDNA plot,

353
00:20:07.408 --> 00:20:08.888
and I think we're going to talk more about that later.

354
00:20:09.288 --> 00:20:12.618
We don't know whether we'll just have a cheaper way to measure tumor burden or

355
00:20:12.628 --> 00:20:14.558
we're measuring something about the biology or both.

356
00:20:15.008 --> 00:20:18.748
But one thing that's very curious is we have a cohort of 200 patients with colon

357
00:20:18.828 --> 00:20:20.948
cancer that we've immunostained for OR1.

358
00:20:20.968 --> 00:20:24.237
The 10% or so who had the lowest level that was either undetectable or

359
00:20:24.308 --> 00:20:27.408
questionable, no one has died yet. So we don't know.

360
00:20:28.088 --> 00:20:31.358
We don't have the power yet to do multivariate on that cohort, but we think it's

361
00:20:31.388 --> 00:20:34.828
interesting and potentially useful and may represent something about the

362
00:20:34.848 --> 00:20:38.488
biology. Finally, we took this best bar-coded mosaic assay

363
00:20:38.588 --> 00:20:42.288
over 288 samples from a gastroesophageal trial from

364
00:20:42.348 --> 00:20:43.968
Ji-Youn Lee at Samsung Medical Center.

365
00:20:44.468 --> 00:20:48.208
We can detect about two-thirds of the patients with the SIMOA, but we can actually

366
00:20:48.228 --> 00:20:50.248
detect everybody with the mosaic assay.

367
00:20:50.768 --> 00:20:53.368
And when we look at these patients over their clinical

368
00:20:53.468 --> 00:20:57.288
course at baseline, where they clearly fall during

369
00:20:57.348 --> 00:21:01.288
therapy and where many of them increase afterwards, we can see that the

370
00:21:01.328 --> 00:21:04.968
mosaic assay lets us measure the nadirs better than the

371
00:21:04.988 --> 00:21:07.468
SIMOA assay. And we're still doing the work to figure out if this improved

372
00:21:07.528 --> 00:21:08.488
sensitivity matters.

373
00:21:10.008 --> 00:21:13.797
And finally, in Sam Klempner's trial at Mass General with Sam and

374
00:21:13.848 --> 00:21:17.468
Matt, we have a 41-patient trial with Nilotrifax, which is

375
00:21:18.008 --> 00:21:21.778
a liposomal fulviranox regimen. And we had samples at

376
00:21:21.808 --> 00:21:25.797
pre-therapy cycle one, day eight, which is after just a single dose of

377
00:21:25.828 --> 00:21:29.608
chemo, and then post-op. And the responders are very, very strongly

378
00:21:29.708 --> 00:21:31.158
segregated from the non-responders.

379
00:21:31.228 --> 00:21:34.368
P-value is less than 0.001 after a single dose of chemotherapy.

380
00:21:34.808 --> 00:21:38.278
So gastroesophageal cancer doesn't have any pervasive biomarker up till now.

381
00:21:38.278 --> 00:21:41.508
We're very excited about this. We need to do a lot more work with the time points.

382
00:21:41.528 --> 00:21:44.348
We're comparing it against ctDNA to see if it's additive,

383
00:21:45.228 --> 00:21:48.848
and we're trying to understand exactly what's going on in detail at the tissue

384
00:21:48.888 --> 00:21:52.668
level. So to wrap up, the current status is that OR1 is

385
00:21:52.708 --> 00:21:55.868
expressed-- Sorry, it's a lot of text on this slide, but that OR1 is expressed in

386
00:21:55.908 --> 00:21:59.147
tissue from cancers and high-risk precursors across organ systems.

387
00:21:59.548 --> 00:22:02.848
It appears useful with a limited number of early cases that we have done to

388
00:22:02.948 --> 00:22:06.888
date. It's highly specific, it's low cost,

389
00:22:07.097 --> 00:22:10.828
and it's fast, and it's cheap. It can also be multiplexed using the bar-coded

390
00:22:10.868 --> 00:22:14.748
mosaic technology. So what we need to do to see if this is actually useful

391
00:22:14.788 --> 00:22:16.608
is of course run a lot more samples.

392
00:22:16.978 --> 00:22:20.788
We need to know-- We don't yet have any evidence that there is a normal level of

393
00:22:20.828 --> 00:22:24.818
OR1 in the blood, but we have to figure out if there is, and that's going

394
00:22:24.828 --> 00:22:28.728
to take thousands of samples. We also want to study other biofluids and proximal

395
00:22:28.828 --> 00:22:32.668
samples, as I mentioned, like stool and pap and oral

396
00:22:32.768 --> 00:22:36.358
swabs. And if you have a cohort and you want to know if OR1 could be useful, we

397
00:22:36.368 --> 00:22:38.648
would love to collaborate, so please reach out.

398
00:22:39.048 --> 00:22:43.008
So to summarize, OR1 is a pervasive and specific cancer biomarker due to unique

399
00:22:43.048 --> 00:22:46.608
transposon biology. It's pervasively expressed in cancer and high-risk

400
00:22:46.688 --> 00:22:47.328
precursors.

401
00:22:48.288 --> 00:22:51.938
Separately from this, we're very interested in LINE1 as a potential driver of

402
00:22:51.968 --> 00:22:55.738
cancer that could be targetable. LINE1 and HIV have a shared evolutionary history,

403
00:22:55.748 --> 00:22:58.208
and HIV reverse transcriptase inhibitors inhibit LINE1.

404
00:22:58.748 --> 00:23:02.548
Separate topic for another day. We've made ultrasensitive single

405
00:23:02.608 --> 00:23:05.907
molecule mosaic assays. We can detect OR1 in plasma.

406
00:23:06.278 --> 00:23:09.808
We hope in other biofluids. The assays are under $3 in consumables.

407
00:23:09.868 --> 00:23:13.588
We can run them in two hours. They are sensitive and specific, and they're

408
00:23:13.628 --> 00:23:16.228
likely orthogonal to other methods like ctDNA.

409
00:23:16.278 --> 00:23:18.988
And I guess when I say we, I mean Carly Rubound, who's sitting here in the room.

410
00:23:20.488 --> 00:23:22.848
They appear useful in cancer detection.

411
00:23:22.888 --> 00:23:26.488
They could either be a standalone test or part of a tiered screening algorithm,

412
00:23:27.488 --> 00:23:31.398
where you could repeat samples in longitudinal monitoring or start with OR1

413
00:23:31.408 --> 00:23:35.048
at the start of a screen and follow up with a more expensive test in an MSAT

414
00:23:35.088 --> 00:23:37.948
modality.So thanks everybody for your attention.

415
00:23:38.268 --> 00:23:41.678
I want to thank especially David Walt and Kathy Burns, who've been supporting and

416
00:23:41.708 --> 00:23:45.408
leading this project with me. Fazilat Yilmaz from the staining, Stefan Konney

417
00:23:45.448 --> 00:23:48.748
from David's lab, Mike Rout and Peter Friddy, who made the

418
00:23:48.808 --> 00:23:52.338
nanobodies, Ben Greenbaum, who has done a lot of support of computation,

419
00:23:52.427 --> 00:23:56.188
Tatjana, who did the multivariate analysis, John

420
00:23:56.208 --> 00:24:00.028
Licava, who developed a lot of the reagents with me, Ji-Yun Li with samples, and

421
00:24:00.068 --> 00:24:03.978
many people at MGH, including David Ting, Sam Klempner, Andy Chan, and

422
00:24:03.988 --> 00:24:05.268
Matt Strickland. Thanks so much.

423
00:24:10.928 --> 00:24:12.788
Dr. Taylor, that was an excellent talk.

424
00:24:13.008 --> 00:24:16.848
I'm going to ask you to come out of your slides so we can put the QR code

425
00:24:16.908 --> 00:24:18.468
up there again, if that's possible.

426
00:24:18.808 --> 00:24:21.948
While folks are making their way to the microphone or

427
00:24:23.088 --> 00:24:26.928
using the code, I'm going to take chair's privilege to

428
00:24:26.948 --> 00:24:29.608
start with the questions. It's a really exciting topic.

429
00:24:29.648 --> 00:24:33.508
It's something that we've been interested in for a while

430
00:24:33.568 --> 00:24:37.008
now, too. It seems that the proportion of cancers

431
00:24:37.128 --> 00:24:40.768
that are positive for LINE1 antibody in the

432
00:24:40.988 --> 00:24:44.908
pathology assays sort of correlate with the P53 positivity, and

433
00:24:44.928 --> 00:24:48.848
so do you think these really are sort of hand-in-hand as far as the utility

434
00:24:48.888 --> 00:24:52.568
of LINE1 for early detection will be in those cancers that tend to be more

435
00:24:52.608 --> 00:24:53.527
P53 mutant?

436
00:24:54.368 --> 00:24:58.348
For sure. So it's been well established for a long time that P53 is a tumor

437
00:24:58.408 --> 00:25:02.168
suppressor. Actually, there's really nice work from John Abrams' lab that P53

438
00:25:02.208 --> 00:25:06.008
evolved before multicellular organisms to suppress transposons and only later

439
00:25:06.028 --> 00:25:07.788
developed many of the roles that we know and love.

440
00:25:09.628 --> 00:25:13.508
It is very clear that LINE1 is on before P53 mutation, and what we think is going

441
00:25:13.588 --> 00:25:17.508
on is a three-step process where early epigenetic de-repression turns

442
00:25:17.548 --> 00:25:21.388
on LINE1. Actually, P53 mutation alone is not sufficient to de-repress LINE1.

443
00:25:21.948 --> 00:25:25.648
And then LINE1 does these number of bad activities, including

444
00:25:25.708 --> 00:25:28.648
selecting for the P53 mutation, we think.

445
00:25:29.028 --> 00:25:31.947
And that together then results in a P53 mutation.

446
00:25:31.968 --> 00:25:35.708
And once P53 is mutated, very clearly LINE1 levels

447
00:25:35.748 --> 00:25:39.488
increase, and the cell's ability to survive LINE1-mediated DNA damage

448
00:25:39.568 --> 00:25:41.648
increase, so the mutagen burden increases.

449
00:25:41.688 --> 00:25:45.188
So both the protein and the genomic lesions increase really dramatically

450
00:25:45.688 --> 00:25:49.228
to the point that Ben Greenbaum's lab can actually predict not just if your P53

451
00:25:49.288 --> 00:25:53.248
mutated, but what kind of P53 mutation you have, because

452
00:25:53.268 --> 00:25:56.868
the amount of residual function really strongly predicts how much genomic damage

453
00:25:56.928 --> 00:25:57.608
LINE1 can do.

454
00:25:58.688 --> 00:26:02.628
So yeah, I think it will be most useful in P53 mutant cancers, which

455
